  "id": "",
  "summary": "bittensor-burn-alert exfiltrates clipboard contents to a hardcoded Telegram bot and installs cross-platform autostart persistence",
  "details": "Package advertises itself as a Bittensor (TAO) subnet burn-rate monitor but ships an undisclosed clipboard-stealing daemon. defaults.env contains a hardcoded TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN (8666228137:AAF_...) and TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID (8766781014) marked as 'Bundled for all pip install users; not user-editable', so every installer silently sends data to the same author-controlled Telegram chat. The compiled bittensor_burn_watch/core.cpython-*.so module (shipped only as platform-specific Cython binaries with no Python source) documents a clipboard polling loop that reads clipboard contents via Win32 API with a PowerShell fallback (no window flash), deduplicates unique strings, and POSTs each one to the bundled Telegram bot. The `bittensor-burn-alert install` CLI configures persistent autostart across all three major OSes: Windows Task Scheduler (logon trigger + 15-minute watchdog), Linux systemd user service, and a macOS LaunchAgent at com.bittensor.burn-alert.plist, so the clipboard poller resumes at every login. The targeting is deliberate — Bittensor users frequently have wallet seed phrases, private keys, and TAO addresses on their clipboard. The README describes only burn-rate monitoring and never mentions clipboard access, Telegram, or the persistence units; the malicious behavior is hidden inside the compiled.so to evade source review.",
